\subsection*{Cryogenic temperatures}

As pointed out in the previous subsection, an estimate (valid for a sufficiently large atom density) of the scale of the time $\tau_c$ until the creation of the first contaminant atom is \cite{AB}

\begin{displaymath}
\tau_c = \frac{4\delta^2}{\Omega^2}\frac{\tau_0}{b_{nL}N_{\beta}},
\end{displaymath}

\noindent
where $N_{\beta}$ is the number of atoms per effective interaction volume $\beta$, and $b_{nL}$ is the sum of the branching ratios from the $nL$ Rydberg state to the contaminant states that contribute the most to the value of $\beta$. $\tau_0$ is the natural lifetime of the  $nL$  state.

The time $\tau_c$ depends on the ambient temperature $T$ through $\tau_0$ and $b_{nL}$. Figs \ref{fig:cthcal1_4} and \ref{fig:cthcal2_4} show this dependence for some $^{87}$Rb $nS$ Rydberg states. These plots were obtained using the estimates from [302] and the quasiclassical formulas in [303]. We also estimated the largest value $T_N^*$ of the temperature $T$ needed to compensate for the avalanche dephasing effect as a function of $N_{\beta}$, fig. \ref{fig:cthcal3_4}.

\begin{figure}[]
\begin{minipage}[c][4.6cm][t]{.24\textwidth}
