\end{figure}

Some Rydberg-dressing proposals \cite{pupillo2010},\cite{Glaetzle2012},\cite{Bouchoule2002}, \cite{Glaetzle2014} and previous experimental setups [306] making use of systems with an \textit{effective} $N_{\beta}\sim$ 30-70 would need an ambient temperature between just above 10 K to make up for the dephasing effect. The effects on those with a low atom number $N\sim 10$ \cite{vanBijnen2015}, \cite{Lee2013a} should become negligible for cryogenic temperatures around 70 K.

For several proposals the atom number $N_0$ is $\gtrsim 100$ [\cite{honer10a},\cite{maucher2011}] but the van der Waals blockade radius is larger than or comparable to the sample dimensions. They will not be considerably affected by this dephasing process even if not working in a cryogenic environment.

